{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594505"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:48:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:48:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15318"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15318"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.05,0.11,0.26,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64681"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21397"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64681"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is a chronic liver disease characterised by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts. The condition is associated with an increased risk of malignancy in 4-20% of these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following malignancies is most strongly associated with primary sclerosing cholangitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholangiocarcinoma","Colorectal carcinoma","Gallbladder carcinoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Pancreatic adenocarcinoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is most strongly associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Echolangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The chronic inflammation and fibrosis of bile ducts creates an environment that promotes malignant transformation of cholangiocytes. While PSC patients may have a slightly increased risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Egallbladder carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolorectal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, cholangiocarcinoma is by far the most significant malignant complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lifetime risk of developing cholangiocarcinoma in PSC patients is approximately 10-15%. This high risk necessitates regular surveillance with imaging and tumour markers. The prognosis of PSC-associated cholangiocarcinoma is generally poor, with early detection being crucial for improved outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) significantly increases the risk of cholangiocarcinoma.","The lifetime risk of cholangiocarcinoma in PSC patients is 10-15%.","PSC patients require regular surveillance for malignancy development."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scie